## 🌳 The Document Object Model

The DOM is how browsers represent your HTML. JavaScript can reach into this tree and change anything in real-time.

---

## 1️⃣ Selecting Elements

*   `document.getElementById('id')`: Fastest lookup.
*   `document.querySelector('.class')`: Most flexible. Uses CSS selectors.
*   `document.querySelectorAll('...')`: Returns a list (NodeList) of all matching elements.

---

## 2️⃣ Modifying Content & Styles

```javascript
const title = document.querySelector('h1');
title.textContent = "Hello World!";
title.style.color = "blue";
title.classList.add('active');
```

---

## 3️⃣ Event Listeners: The Interaction

We don't use `onclick="..."` in HTML anymore. We attach listeners in JS:

```javascript
const button = document.querySelector('#btn');
button.addEventListener('click', (event) => {
  console.log("Clicked!");
});
```

---

## 🚀 Why This Matters
While React handles much of this for us later, understanding the native DOM is what separates a "component-adder" from a "software engineer."
